<HL> Bonds of Guam, Northern Marianas Aren't Tax Exempt </HL>
<AUTHOR> John Connor (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> TAXES FREST </CO>
<IN> BON </IN>
<G> IRS </G>
<DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>Internal Revenue Service</ORGANIZATION> notified <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Northern Mariana Islands</LOCATION> that interest on <MONEY>$380 million</MONEY> of municipal bonds issued by the two <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION> jurisdictions isn't tax-exempt. 

   But the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> made it clear it hasn't reached the point of moving to tax interest income earned by bondholders. 

   The Territory of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> sold <MONEY>$300 million</MONEY> of bonds as tax-exempt securities in <DATE>October 1985</DATE>. 
The Commonwealth of the <ORGANIZATION>Northern Mariana Islands</ORGANIZATION> sold <MONEY>$80 million</MONEY> of bonds as tax-exempts in <DATE>December 1984</DATE>. 
Both issues were underwritten by <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright Inc</ORGANIZATION>. 

   A <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> grand jury in <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> late last year cited the <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Northern Mariana Islands</LOCATION> bond issues, among others, in a 52-count indictment charging <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright Executive</ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON>Arthur Abba Goldberg</PERSON> and a one-time company consultant with promoting a nationwide fraud involving more than <MONEY>$2 billion</MONEY> in municipal bonds. 
<PERSON>Mr. Goldberg</PERSON> has pleaded innocent. 
His trial isn't expected to get under way until next year. 
The company has denied any wrongdoing. 

   "After thorough consideration, we have concluded that interest on the (<LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>) bonds is not tax-exempt under section 103 of the Code," <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON>Lawrence Gibbs</PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION>Guam Gov. Joseph Ada</ORGANIZATION> in a letter. 
The same message was delivered to Gov. <PERSON>Pedro Tenorio</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Northern Mariana Islands</ORGANIZATION>. 

   The action wasn't wholly unexpected. 
Gov. <ORGANIZATION>Ada</ORGANIZATION> told a congressional panel earlier this year that the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> was going to declare the <MONEY>$300 million</MONEY> issue taxable. 

   <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> officials have refused to discuss the bonds in question, and a spokesman declined yesterday to comment on the issues. 
Officials of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Northern Mariana Islands</ORGANIZATION> couldn't be reached immediately for comment. 

   Attorney <PERSON>David Aufhauser</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Williams &amp; Connolly, Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION>'s law firm, emphasized the view that the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION>'s conclusions are "only preliminary." 
He said <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION> is confident the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION>'s conclusions will be "reconsidered and changed" in due course. 

   The <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> said in the letters, "If desired, we will also consider whether there are good and sufficient reasons for finally resolving this matter through the use of a closing agreement," explaining that under such agreements, "the service forgoes taxing the interest in the hands of the bondholder but collects all or an appropriate percentage of such lost revenues from the issuer." 

   Guam and the <ORGANIZATION>Northern Mariana Islands</ORGANIZATION> separately have filed lawsuits against parties involved in the issuance of the bonds, including <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION>. 

</TEXT>
