<FIRST>u i PM-TyphoonJack 1stLd-Writethru a0498 12-26 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Typhoon Jack, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0498,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Powerful Typhoon Threatens Guam, Saipan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with typhoon weakening, new course to miss
Saipan. No pickup. Note Wednesday in 2nd graf is cq; `today' in 7th graf
refers to Tuesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGANA, Guam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> territory were advised
to stock up on emergency supplies as a powerful typhoon stalled 200
miles to the east.
   Typhoon <PERSON>Jack</PERSON>, unusually late in the season for a major storm,
had sustained winds of 125 mph with gusts to 155 mph at <TIME>1 a.m.</TIME>
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE> and was gradually weakening, according to the <ORGANIZATION>Joint
Typhoon Warning Center</ORGANIZATION>.
   Forecasters said the typhoon was expected to drift slowly toward
the northwest during the <DATE>next 18</DATE> to 24 hours on a course that would
take it 57 miles north of <LOCATION>Saipan</LOCATION>.
   Before it stalled in the western <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION>, the storm had been on
a track that would take it between <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Saipan</LOCATION>, the capital of
the Commonwealth of the <LOCATION>Northern Mariana Islands</LOCATION> north of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>.
   ``The potential for erratic movement is high,'' said hourly
advisories issued by the center.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> sent B-52 bombers to <LOCATION>Okinawa</LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> ordered
its large ships to sea to ride out the storm, officials said.
   Banks closed today and the 125,000 residents of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> and the
30,000 people on <LOCATION>Saipan</LOCATION> were advised to get supplies of food,
water, batteries and the like.
   Guam is under a Tropical Cyclone Condition 2, meaning a storm
could hit the island within 24 hours.
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC>
