<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--TyphoonJack 1stLd-Writethru a0469 12-27 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Typhoon Jack, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0469,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Typhoon Jack Weakens, But Still Threatens Guam</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf with 2 grafs to update position, weakening.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGANA, Guam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weakening Typhoon <PERSON>Jack</PERSON> began to drift
toward this <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> territory in the western <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION> <DATE>today</DATE> and was
forecast to at least brush the island on <DATE>Friday</DATE>, according to civil
defense officials.
   At <TIME>1 a.m.</TIME> <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, (<TIME>10 a.m.</TIME> <DATE>today</DATE> EST), the storm was 190 miles
east of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>, moving west-southwest at about 3 mph. Its sustained
wind speed was 85 mph with gusts to 100 mph. On <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, its
sustained winds were 135.
   Lt. <PERSON>Richard Bouchard</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Joint Typhoon Warning Center</ORGANIZATION> here
said at the rate the storm was weakening it could lose typhoon
status _ sustained wind speed of at least 74 mph _ before it passes
south of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>.
   ``Forecasters can't determine how close it will come, but it's
expected to pass <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> during the day <DATE>Friday</DATE>,'' said <PERSON>George Toves</PERSON>, a
<ORGANIZATION>Guam Civil Defense</ORGANIZATION> officer. ``We'll get some portion of it.''
   The storm had been stalled about 200 miles east of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> since
early <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC>
