<FIRST>d i PM-BRF--PacificStorm     10-02 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Pacific Storm,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Territory Prepares for Colleen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGANA, Guam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical Storm <PERSON>Colleen</PERSON> moved toward this <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
territory and the Commonwealth of the <ORGANIZATION>Northern Mariana Islands</ORGANIZATION>
packing winds up to 45 mph.
   Colleen was expected to intensify to typhoon status, with 75 mph
winds, when it sweeps within 70 miles south of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, the
<ORGANIZATION>Joint Typhoon Warning Center</ORGANIZATION> said.
   At <TIME>1 p.m.</TIME> <DATE>today</DATE> (<TIME>10 p.m.</TIME> <DATE>Sunday</DATE> EDT), <PERSON>Colleen</PERSON> was at 11.5
degrees latitude and 148.6 degrees longitude, or 247 miles
east-southeast of <ORGANIZATION>Andersen Air Force Base</ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>, the center said.
   As of <TIME>3 p.m.</TIME>, maximum winds were 40 to 45 mph and the storm was
moving to the west-northwest at 12 to 14 mph.
   Guam's <ORGANIZATION>Civil Defense</ORGANIZATION> issued a tropical-storm alert and said
<PERSON>Colleen</PERSON> could hit the island within 72 hours.
   Military officials were meeting to determine when airplanes and
ships should be moved for protection.
   The storm formed <DATE>Sunday</DATE> 500 miles east of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>.
   The term ``typhoon'' is used for hurricanes west of the
international date line.
</TEXT>
