<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tropical Storm Off Guam Upgraded To Typhoon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with storm upgraded to typhoon,
details. Pickup 7th graf `All Navy...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AGANA, Guam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical storm Koryn became a full-fledged
typhoon <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, lashing this <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> Pacific territory with strong
winds and heavy rains, toppling trees and flooding low-lying areas,
authorities said.
   There were no immediate reports of injuries or damage to
structures.
   As of <TIME>5 p.m.</TIME> (<TIME>2 a.m. EST</TIME>), <PERSON>Koryn</PERSON> had sustained winds of 75 mph,
with gusts to 90 mph, according to <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON>Joe Atangan</PERSON> of the
<ORGANIZATION>Joint Typhoon Warning Center Rapid Response Team</ORGANIZATION>.
   The storm's center was located 45 miles east of the northern tip
of the island, where <ORGANIZATION>Andersen Air Force Base</ORGANIZATION> is located, <PERSON>Atangan</PERSON>
said.
   The typhoon was ``quasi stationary'' but was expected to move
off to the north-northwest, skirting the northern coast, he said.
   Guam and the <ORGANIZATION>Northern Mariana Islands</ORGANIZATION> remained under a typhoon
alert, although the projected path of the storm would take it south
of the <LOCATION>Marianas</LOCATION> and away from any other islands, <PERSON>Atangan</PERSON> said.
   There were reports on <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> of intermittent power outages because
of downed lines, and flooding was reported in many areas, the
<ORGANIZATION>Pacific Daily News</ORGANIZATION> said.
   ``There's lots of coconuts on the roads,'' <PERSON>Atangan</PERSON> said.
   All <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> aircraft were placed in hangers for protection against
the strong winds, and the USS Haleakala was sent out to sea to
weather the storm, said Lt. <PERSON>Dave Lee</PERSON>. Three other warships were
allowed to remain in port, he said.
   The 12 planes at <LOCATION>Andersen</LOCATION>, including 11 B-52s, were parked
behind fortifications as the storm approached, said base spokesman
Capt. <PERSON>Wayne Perry</PERSON>.
   A tropical storm has sustained winds ranging from 39 to 73 mph.
A typhoon has a minimum sustained surface wind of 74 mph.
</TEXT>
