<HL> IRS to Make Taxable $300 Million of Bonds, Guam Governor Says </HL>
<AUTHOR> (WSJ Special) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> TAXES FREST </CO>
<IN> BON </IN>
<G> IRS </G>
<DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guam Gov. <PERSON>Joseph Ada</PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION>Internal Revenue Service</ORGANIZATION> soon will declare taxable a <MONEY>$300 million</MONEY> Guam housing-bond issue underwritten by <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright Inc</ORGANIZATION>. 

   Gov. <ORGANIZATION>Ada</ORGANIZATION> told a <ORGANIZATION>House Interior</ORGANIZATION> subcommittee he met with the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> last week on the bonds' tax status, and said, "They are coming out and declaring the <MONEY>$300 million</MONEY> (issue) taxable soon." 

   An attorney for <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION>, a small Wall Street bond house, said he had no information on any <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> decision to tax the <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> bonds. 
A senior <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION> official declined all comment on the matter. 

   The <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> bonds were issued as tax-exempt securities in <DATE>1985</DATE>. 

   Two authorities on municipal bonds said they couldn't remember the <ORGANIZATION>IRS</ORGANIZATION>'s having declared an issue taxable retroactively. 

   "I don't think it has ever happened," said <PERSON>James Lebenthal</PERSON>, president of the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> bond firm <ORGANIZATION>Lebenthal &amp; Co</ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON>Richard Ciccarone</PERSON>, senior research analyst of <ORGANIZATION>Van Kampen Merritt Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ill.</LOCATION>, securities concern, said he couldn't recall it happening in his more than 10 years in the business. 

</TEXT>
