<HEAD>Executive Gets 18 Months in Mail Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Wall Street executive who pleaded guilty to
three counts of mail fraud for for allegedly bribing a former
governor of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> has been sentenced to 18 months in prison.
   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> District <PERSON>Judge Jesse W. Curtis</PERSON> on <DATE>Monday</DATE> also placed <PERSON>Arthur
Abba Goldberg</PERSON> on five years' probation, fined him <MONEY>$100,000</MONEY> and
ordered him to repay the <ORGANIZATION>United States</ORGANIZATION> <MONEY>$300,000</MONEY>.
   <PERSON>Goldberg</PERSON>, executive vice president of the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> bond
underwriting firm of <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION>, pleaded guilty <DATE>July 14</DATE> to
three counts of mail fraud.
   He had been accused of funneling <MONEY>$70,000</MONEY> to former Guam Gov.
<PERSON>Ricardo J. Bordallo</PERSON>'s unsuccessful <DATE>1986</DATE> re-election campaign. In
exchange, <PERSON>Bordallo</PERSON> allegedly agreed to generate support for a <MONEY>$300
million</MONEY> housing bond issue underwritten by <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION>.
   Bordallo was acquitted in <DATE>February 1986</DATE> of accepting bribes from
<PERSON>Goldberg</PERSON> but was convicted on 10 counts of government corruption.
He served as governor from 1975-79 and from 1983-87.
   <PERSON>Goldberg</PERSON> had faced a maximum 15 years' imprisonment and a
<MONEY>$750,000</MONEY> fine in addition to restitution payments, according to
<PERSON>William O'Connor</PERSON>, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> attorney from <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>.
   The three counts referred to money bilked from the <ORGANIZATION>Guam Program
Development Fund</ORGANIZATION> and a ``lulling letter'' assuring fund authorities
that the transactions were legal.
   A <DATE>December 1987</DATE> indictment charged <PERSON>Goldberg</PERSON> with preparing phony
invoices that were sent to the bank entrusted with the fund money.
   The bank paid the money to <PERSON>Goldberg</PERSON>, who spent <MONEY>$25,000</MONEY> to buy
campaign paraphernalia _ including parasols, shirts and hats _ for
<PERSON>Bordallo</PERSON>'s unsuccessful re-election bid, <PERSON>O'Connor</PERSON> has said.
   Authorities said <PERSON>Goldberg</PERSON> made his contributions after <PERSON>Bordallo</PERSON>
was promised that he would receive campaign contributions if he
supported the bond issue to build homes. The bond was approved by
the <ORGANIZATION>Guam Legislature</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1985</DATE>. <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION> has denied any
wrongdoing.
   In exchange for <ORGANIZATION>Goldberg</ORGANIZATION>'s guilty pleas, 46 other counts
alleging bribery, conspiracy, and wire and mail fraud were
dismissed. The case was moved from <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>, 3,800 miles west of
<LOCATION>Hawaii</LOCATION>, because of extensive pretrial publicity on the island.
   Twelve of the original counts against <PERSON>Goldberg</PERSON> were related
directly to <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>. The balance referred to fraud involving the use
of the <ORGANIZATION>Commercial Bank of Americas</ORGANIZATION> in transactions that did not
involve the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> territory.
   In <DATE>August 1987</DATE>, Gov. <PERSON>Joseph Ada</PERSON> sued <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION> for the
return of <MONEY>$14 million</MONEY> in fees the firm had received, as well as
<MONEY>$250 million</MONEY> in punitive damages. <PERSON>O'Connor</PERSON> said in <DATE>July</DATE> the suit
had been settled, but he released no details.
</TEXT>
