<HEAD>Judge Sets Trial Date for Anti-Abortion Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGANA, Guam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on <DATE>Monday</DATE> extended a
restraining order against enforcement of the most restrictive <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
abortion law.
   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> District <PERSON>Judge Alex Munson</PERSON> had issued a temporary
restraining order <DATE>Friday</DATE>, a few hours after a group of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>
residents and medical groups filed a class-action suit. On <DATE>Monday</DATE>,
he extended the order until <DATE>May 8</DATE>, when a trial on the suit is
scheduled to begin.
   ``We're very happy,'' said <PERSON>Anita Arriola</PERSON>, the plaintiffs'
attorney.
   The law prohibits abortions except when a pregnancy endangers
the life of the mother. It makes it a third-degree felony to
perform an abortion or aid in the procedure, a misdemeanor for a
woman to solicit or have an abortion and a misdemeanor for a person
to solicit a woman to have an abortion.
   The law in this <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION> territory is seen by abortion opponents
as a potential vehicle to challenge the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON>Roe
vs. Wade</PERSON> decision that legalized abortion.
   The <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> law provides for a referendum in the <DATE>Nov. 6</DATE> general
election for <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> voters to decide whether to retain or reject the
abortion ban.
   <PERSON>Janet Benshoof</PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION>American Civil Liberties Union's
Reproductive Freedom Project</ORGANIZATION> defied the law <DATE>last Tuesday</DATE> when she
publicly encouraged women seeking abortions to have them done in
<LOCATION>Hawaii</LOCATION>. She was charged in the territorial <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> with
solicitation to commit abortion, a misdemeanor.
   Among those named in the suit is Gov. <PERSON>Joseph Ada</PERSON>, who signed the
measure into law <DATE>March 19</DATE>.
   The plaintiffs include ``<PERSON>Maria Doe</PERSON>,'' a <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> woman who is eight
weeks pregnant and wants an abortion; the <ORGANIZATION>Guam Society</ORGANIZATION> of
Obstetricians and Gynecologists, the <ORGANIZATION>Guam Nurses Association</ORGANIZATION>, an
Episcopal priest and three <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> doctors.
</TEXT>
