<HEAD>10 on Fishing Boat Crew Missing After Typhoon Russ</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS in 3 grafs with search suspended, no sight of missing;
pick up 4th graf, `The Marguarita ...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AGANA, Guam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>Coast Guard</ORGANIZATION> today called off a search for
10 crew members of a South Korean fishing boat missing for three
days since Typhoon <PERSON>Russ</PERSON> swept the area, officials said.
   A military transport ship located the partially submerged hull
of the 68-foot Marguarita I 35 miles off the southern tip of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>
on <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, but there was no sign of the crew, the <ORGANIZATION>Coast Guard</ORGANIZATION> said.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Coast Guard</ORGANIZATION> cutter <LOCATION>Assateague</LOCATION> and a C130 aircraft searched a
19,000-square-mile area but didn't locate any crew members, said
Lt. <PERSON>Bob Ritchie</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Coast Guard Rescue Center</ORGANIZATION> on this <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
island territory in the <LOCATION>Western Pacific</LOCATION>. He said the search was
called off today.
   The Marguarita I sailed from <LOCATION>Agana</LOCATION> on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, even though it
was well known the typhoon was bearing down on the island, said
<ORGANIZATION>Coast Guard</ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON>Jeffrey Lee</PERSON>, duty officer for the <ORGANIZATION>Joint Rescue
Coordination Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Honolulu</LOCATION>.
   The fishing vessel radioed its agent here late <DATE>Thursday</DATE> that it
was disabled with a clutch problem, <PERSON>Lee</PERSON> said.
   Communication with the boat was lost <DATE>Friday</DATE> when electrical
power went out on <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> as Typhoon <PERSON>Russ</PERSON> battered the island with
wind up to 150 mph.
   <ORGANIZATION>Federal Emergency Management Agency</ORGANIZATION> officials said the storm
damged or destroyed more than 2,000 homes and injured 88 people. No
deaths were reported.
   <ORGANIZATION>Guam Power Authority</ORGANIZATION> officials said they expected to have
electrical power restored to <PERCENT>60 percent</PERCENT> of the island today. Water
service remained disrupted in many areas because pumps were without
electrical power.
   Gov. <PERSON>Joseph Ada</PERSON> has asked President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> to declare the island a
disaster area.
</TEXT>
</DOC><DOC>
