<FIRST>r p AM-GuamPrimary     08-31 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guam Primary,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archbishop Encourages Guamanians to Vote Against Pro-Choice
Candidates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGANA, Guam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fight to keep abortion legal on <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> is
being overshadowed in <DATE>Saturday</DATE>'s primary elections by the
possibility that the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> territory may have its first woman and
non-native governor.
   Gov. <PERSON>Joseph Ada</PERSON> is unopposed on the Republican ballot as he
seeks a second term.
   Democrats face a choice between <PERSON>Sen. Madeleine Z. Bordallo</PERSON>, a
native of <LOCATION>Minnesota</LOCATION> and widow of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>'s former governor, or former
Lt. Gov. <PERSON>Rudy Sablan</PERSON>. The winner will face <ORGANIZATION>Ada</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Nov. 6</DATE>.
   Guam's 21-member unicameral legislature unanimously approved a
bill virtually banning abortions <DATE>March 8</DATE> after <PERSON>Archbishop Anthony
Apuron</PERSON> threatened in a television interview to excommunicate any
Roman Catholic senator who voted against it.
   Ada signed the bill into law, saying: ``In my heart, I believe
that a fetus is a human being.''
   The law carried a penalty of up to a year in jail and a <MONEY>$1,000</MONEY>
fine for obtaining an illegal abortion or soliciting a woman to
have an abortion. Performing an illegal abortion was punishable by
up to five years in prison.
   Last week, <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> District <PERSON>Judge Alex Munson</PERSON> struck down the law
as unconstitutional. Munson declared that <PERSON>Roe vs. Wade</PERSON>, the <DATE>1973</DATE>
<ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> decision establishing the right to an abortion,
``applied with equal force and effect to <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>.''
   Ada has not indicated whether he will seek an appeal.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Bordallo</PERSON> has said she also opposes abortion.
   <ORGANIZATION>Ada</ORGANIZATION> said he's running on his record of the past four years. He
said he is confident he and his running mate, Lt. Gov. <PERSON>Frank Blas</PERSON>,
will win re-election.
   On <DATE>Jan. 31</DATE>, <PERSON>Mrs. Bordallo</PERSON>'s husband, <PERSON>Ricardo</PERSON>, chained himself to
a statue, wrapped himself in <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>'s flag and shot himself in the
head. That occurred less than four hours before he was to fly to
<LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> to begin serving a four-year prison term for witness
tampering and obstruction.
   Ada defeated <PERSON>Bordallo</PERSON> in the <DATE>1986</DATE> election after <PERSON>Bordallo</PERSON> had
been indicted on the federal charges.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Bordallo</PERSON> wants to be <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>'s first woman governor and the
first governor who is non-Chamorro, the name for native Guamanians.
   ``Women are moving ahead today. They are leading countries.
Right next door, we have a housewife leading 60 million people,''
said <PERSON>Mrs. Bordallo</PERSON>, referring to Philippine President <PERSON>Corazon
Aquino</PERSON>.
   Some 130,000 people life on <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>, an island about 1,500 miles
east of the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION>.
   <PERSON>Mrs. Bordallo</PERSON>, 57, came to <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> in <DATE>1948</DATE> when her father accepted
a position as principal of <ORGANIZATION>George Washington High School</ORGANIZATION> here.
   <PERSON>Sablan</PERSON>, 58, served as Gov. <PERSON>Bordallo</PERSON>'s lieutenant governor from
<DATE>1974</DATE> to <DATE>1978</DATE>, unsuccessfully challenged <PERSON>Bordallo</PERSON> in the Democratic
primaries in <DATE>1978</DATE> and <DATE>1982</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Sablan</PERSON>, who also opposes abortion, said one of his priorities as
governor would be to set up a territorial tax structure that is not
tied to the federal tax system.
   The archbishop issued a pastoral letter published in newspapers
this week calling for voters to vote down pro-choice candidates.
   ``Like a modern day <ORGANIZATION>Pontius Pilate</ORGANIZATION>, a legislator or official may
attempt to wash his or her hands of abortion,'' <PERSON>Apuron</PERSON> said.
``However, the legislator cannot wash away the blood of the
innocents he or she has consciously declined to protect. Nor can
the voter sit idly by in apathy.''
</TEXT>
