<HEAD>Pacific Islands Representatives Seek Federal Aid to Combat Drug
Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> territories told a
congressional panel <DATE>Thursday</DATE> that they have increasing drug
problems, and need the additional federal aid included in pending
legislation.
   The bill, introduced by Rep. <PERSON>Don de Lugo</PERSON>, D-Virgin Islands,
would provide training, equipment and money for <ORGANIZATION>American Samoa</ORGANIZATION>,
<LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>Northern Mariana Islands</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Puerto Rico</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>U.S. Virgin
Islands</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Palau</ORGANIZATION>.
   De <PERSON>Lugo</PERSON>, who presided at the hearing as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION>House
Interior</ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on insular and international affairs, said he
expected the legislation to become part of a planned comprehensive
drug bill this year.
   The legislation would provide <MONEY>$11.5 million</MONEY> in assistance in the
first year, and <MONEY>$5.5 million</MONEY> annually in subsequent years.
   Gov. <PERSON>Alexander A. Farrelly</PERSON> of the <LOCATION>Virgin Islands</LOCATION> said his
territory has become a major transit point for drugs moving from
<LOCATION>South America</LOCATION> to the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> mainland.
   But the governor and <PERSON>Iver Stridiron</PERSON>, president of the <LOCATION>Virgin
Islands</LOCATION> legislature, said significant amounts of the drugs remain
in the territory and are causing a large increase in violent crimes.
   ``It really has our community under siege,'' <PERSON>Stridiron</PERSON> said. But
he added that with additional resources, the island territory could
become a model of combatting the drug problem in <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> territories.
   Farrelly said his major problem is resources, commenting that
the assignment of a single <ORGANIZATION>Drug Enforcement Administration</ORGANIZATION> agent in
the islands indicates either ``non-recognition of a serious
problem'' or lack of interest in solving it.
   Gov. <PERSON>Joseph F. Ada</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> said his territory is experiencing a
resurgence of heroin abuse after cleaning up the problem following
the <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> War.
   ``In <DATE>1985</DATE>, there was not one single case of heroin possession in
the territory of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>,'' he testified. ``In <DATE>1986</DATE>, 12 heroin arrests
were made by our police department.
   ``In <DATE>1987</DATE>, there were 108 cases of heroin possession, with 56
still pending laboratory analysis and confirmation. By any
definition, this is an alarming rise,'' <ORGANIZATION>Ada</ORGANIZATION> said.
   The governor said <PERCENT>91 percent</PERCENT> pure heroin from <LOCATION>Southeast Asia</LOCATION> has
been entering <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> through <ORGANIZATION>Palau</ORGANIZATION>. But after law enforcement
officers discovered the route, the drugs began coming to <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> via
the <LOCATION>Northern Marianas</LOCATION>, he said.
   Asked by de <PERSON>Lugo</PERSON> if he could put a cost on <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>'s drug problem,
<ORGANIZATION>Ada</ORGANIZATION> said the law enforcement price tag could be <MONEY>$2 million</MONEY> to <MONEY>$3
million</MONEY>, but added the real cost could only be measured in trauma
and shattered lives _ not dollars.
   Responding to a question by Rep. <PERSON>Fofo I.F. Sunia</PERSON>, D-American
<LOCATION>Samoa</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Ada</ORGANIZATION> said he would fire anyone in his administration abusing
drugs with ``no questions asked.''
   A written statement submitted by <ORGANIZATION>American Samoa</ORGANIZATION> Gov. <PERSON>A.P. Lutali</PERSON>
said the ``most pervasive and growing illegal substance abuse
problem'' in his territory is marijuana, followed by cocaine.
   Referring to the marijuana problem, <PERSON>Lutali</PERSON>'s statement said,
``What 10 years ago was a situation involving a relatively small
number of individuals importing the drug through the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> mail has
now become a cultivation enterprises market by extended families
producing in excess of seven tons per year.''
</TEXT>
