<HL> Goldberg Pleads Innocent In Guam Bond Fraud Case </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> MW FREST </CO>
<IN> BON </IN>
<DATELINE> AGANA, Guam (AP)  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Arthur Abba Goldberg</PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> bond underwriting firm, pleaded innocent to charges he orchestrated a bogus <MONEY>$300 million</MONEY> bond issue on <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>. 

   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> District <PERSON>Judge Cristobal Duenas</PERSON> allowed <PERSON>Mr. Goldberg</PERSON> to be freed on a <MONEY>$1 million</MONEY> unsecured bond. 
He is represented by <ORGANIZATION>Stanley S. Arkin</ORGANIZATION>. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Goldberg</PERSON> and <PERSON>Frederick L. Mann</PERSON>, a Canadian citizen and former consultant to <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION>, were indicted <DATE>Dec. 10</DATE> on 52 counts of bribery, conspiracy, wire fraud and mail fruad, and violation of interstate anti-racketeering statutes in a scheme to amass more than <MONEY>$2.5 billion</MONEY> in fraudulent bond issues in <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Palau</LOCATION>, the Commonwealth of the <LOCATION>Northern Marianas</LOCATION> and cities across the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> 

   <PERSON>Mr. Mann</PERSON>, who also was scheduled for arraignment yesterday, did not appear. 
Prosecutors said they did not know his whereabouts. 

   <PERSON>Edward K. Strauss</PERSON>, legal counsel to <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION> on the <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> bond, pleaded guilty last week to a charge of withholding knowledge of Messrs. 
<PERSON>Goldberg</PERSON>'s and <PERSON>Mann</PERSON>'s actions. 
He agreed to disclose knowledge of their alleged schemes in exchange for a recommendation of no prison term. 

</TEXT>
