<HEAD>Bush Picks Up Four Territorial Votes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGANA, Guam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four delegates were chosen today to represent
this <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> territory at the <ORGANIZATION>Republican National Convention</ORGANIZATION> and all
say they support Vice President <PERSON>George Bush</PERSON> for president.
   Those selected at the territory's Republican convention included
territorial Gov. <PERSON>Joseph F. Ada</PERSON>, who said of <PERSON>Bush</PERSON>: ``He knows where
<LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> is. His heart is in <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>. He told me that one of these days
the people of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> are going to vote for president.''
   Although residents of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> are American citizens, they are not
allowed to cast ballots in presidential elections.
   <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> said of the <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> results: ``This victory is a tribute to
the hard work and dedication of our organization there.''
   About 200 party members who attended the <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> gathering approved
a number of resolutions that will be given to all <ORGANIZATION>GOP</ORGANIZATION> presidential
candidates.
   One of the resolutions supports the drive to give territorial
residents the right to vote in presidential elections, while
another presses for <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> to become a commonwealth of the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
