<HEAD>Typhoon Percy Heads For Philippines, Gains Speed After Striking
Palau</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with typhoon picking up speed,
moving closer to Philippines. Pickup pvs 5th graf, `Storm
signals...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Typhoon Percy battered the <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION>
island of Palau and then roared <DATE>Sunday</DATE> toward the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION>,
where 30 people were killed in a tropical storm last week.
   One child was killed on <ORGANIZATION>Palau</ORGANIZATION>, a newspaper said.
   The <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION> weather bureau reported at <TIME>5 a.m.</TIME> <DATE>Monday</DATE> that <PERSON>Percy</PERSON>,
packing 93 mph winds, was centered about 465 miles east of the
Philippine island of Samar.
   Percy was moving west-northwest at about 19 mph toward the
islands of <LOCATION>Catanduanes</LOCATION> and southeastern <LOCATION>Luzon island</LOCATION>, which were
expected to feel the effects of the storm late <DATE>Monday</DATE>, the weather
bureau said.
   Storm signals were raised over southeastern <LOCATION>Luzon</LOCATION> and the
central <LOCATION>Visayas</LOCATION> island chain, which includes Samar.
   In <ORGANIZATION>Palau</ORGANIZATION>, a young boy died <DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> when he was swept by
rain into mangrove trees near his home in the cluster of islands
that comprise <ORGANIZATION>Palau</ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Pacific Daily News of Guam</ORGANIZATION> reported.
   The storm passed 90 miles north of <LOCATION>Palau</LOCATION>, which is 800 miles
south of <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION>Joint Typhoon Warning Center</ORGANIZATION>.
   Wind gusts of up to 103 mph blew off tin roofs of many buildings
and knocked radio and television stations off the air, the <ORGANIZATION>Pacific
Daily News</ORGANIZATION> said.
   Airline flights into the republic were canceled, the newspaper
said.
   Earlier <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, the typhoon's winds battered <LOCATION>Yap Island</LOCATION> in the
neighboring <LOCATION>Federated States of Micronesia</LOCATION>, collapsing about 30
houses and damaging banana and coconut plantations, police said.
There were no reports of injuries on Yap.
   On <DATE>Friday</DATE>, <LOCATION>Typhoon Ofelia</LOCATION> swept over the eastern coast of <LOCATION>Luzon</LOCATION>,
the main Philippine island, then struck <LOCATION>Taiwan</LOCATION>. Officials said at
least 30 people were killed in the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> and at least seven
in <LOCATION>Taiwan</LOCATION>.
   More than 84,000 people in the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> were forced to flee
their homes because of flooding and landslides touched off by
<LOCATION>Ofelia</LOCATION>, officials said. Officials were still assessing damage to
crops and infrastructure.
   About 20 typhoons and tropical storms strike the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION>
each year.
</TEXT>
