<HEAD>Guam Says Roe vs. Wade Doesn't Apply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGANA, Guam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. <PERSON>Joseph Ada</PERSON>'s chief counsel contends in
court papers that the <DATE>1973</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> decision guaranteeing
the right to an abortion does not apply to this <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> territory.
   The memorandum argued that <PERSON>Roe vs. Wade</PERSON> and <PERSON>Webster</PERSON> v.
<ORGANIZATION>Reproductive Health Services</ORGANIZATION>, the <DATE>July</DATE> decision giving states more
authority to restrict abortion without overturning the earier
ruling, are not in force in <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> because it is a territory.
   Ada signed the nation's most restrictive anti-abortion measure
into law last month. Enforcement remains on hold pending a hearing
in federal court <DATE>May 8</DATE> on a challenge brought by a woman who wants
an abortion.
   <PERSON>Katherine Maraman</PERSON>, the governor's legal counsel, and attorney
<PERSON>Monessa Lujan</PERSON> argued that many of the Constitution's due process
and equal-protection provisions do not fully apply to <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> in
recognition of its traditions.
   The new law, if upheld by the court, would make it a felony for
doctors to perform abortions and a misdemeanor for women to have
abortions, except in cases where the pregnancy would endanger the
mother's life.
   The measure also makes it a misdemeanor to solicit women to have
an abortion.
</TEXT>
