<HL> Matthews &amp; Wright May Face Charges Of Bond-Market Abuses, Sources Say </HL>
<AUTHOR> John Connor and Thomas E. Ricks (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> MW </CO>
<IN> BON SCR </IN>
<G> SEC </G>
<DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>Securities and Exchange Commission</ORGANIZATION> voted to authorize its staff to charge <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright Group Inc.</ORGANIZATION> and several officers of that bond house with fraud and other securities law violations, according to people familiar with the situation. 

   The action occurred <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> at a closed meeting and wasn't announced. 
It authorizes the <ORGANIZATION>SEC</ORGANIZATION>'s enforcement staff to enter into settlement negotiations and, if those fail, to file suit alleging a host of violations in connection with <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION>'s role as underwriter of more than <MONEY>$1 billion</MONEY> of municipal bonds and as issuer of its own stock, the individuals said. 

   The vote, though unannounced, appears to kick off a kind of fall offensive by the <ORGANIZATION>SEC</ORGANIZATION> against abuses in the municipal-bond market. 
The agency is scheduled to release today the results of its investigation into <ORGANIZATION>Washington Public Power Supply System</ORGANIZATION>'s gigantic 1983 <MONEY>$2.25 billion</MONEY> municipal-bond default. 
It also plans today to decide in an open meeting whether to release a broader report on the municipal-bond market in general, perhaps to demonstrate that the <ORGANIZATION>WPPSS</ORGANIZATION> case isn't an anomaly, as some on Wall Street contend. 
Finally, it will vote on whether to propose for comment a rule designed to enhance disclosure in the municipal market. 

   By taking action against <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION> and proposing changes in the way the municipal-bond market works, the <ORGANIZATION>SEC</ORGANIZATION> may hope to assuage some in <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> who expressed outrage when it was reported this year that the commission had rejected its staff's recommendation to bring charges in the <ORGANIZATION>WPPSS</ORGANIZATION> matter. 

   <PERSON>Gary Lynch</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>SEC</ORGANIZATION>'s enforcement chief, couldn't be reached for comment. 
An agency spokeswoman declined to comment. 

   <PERSON>David Aufhauser</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION> attorney, said, "I've had discussions with the commission staff, but I can't comment beyond that." 
<ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION> has consistently denied any wrongdoing, and insists that all its municipal-bond underwritings conformed with industry practices. 

   The <ORGANIZATION>SEC</ORGANIZATION>'s charges pertain to about 25 municipal-bond deals underwritten by <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1985</DATE> and <DATE>1986</DATE>, and to an offering of 1.5 million shares of its stock in <DATE>August 1986</DATE>. 
The <ORGANIZATION>SEC</ORGANIZATION> case doesn't include <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION>'s best-known deals, the <MONEY>$380 million</MONEY> of controversial issues underwritten for <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Northern Mariana Islands</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1984</DATE> and <DATE>1985</DATE>. 

   The agency may have chosen not to include the <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION> issues in part because they are being scrutinized by other arms of the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> government. 

   Last year, a federal grand jury in <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> charged <PERSON>Arthur Abba Goldberg</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION>'s executive vice president, with fraud, bribery and obstruction of justice. 
<PERSON>Mr. Goldberg</PERSON>, who is on a voluntary leave of absence from the firm, pleaded innocent, and is scheduled to go on trial in <DATE>January</DATE>. 

   Last month, the <ORGANIZATION>Internal Revenue Service</ORGANIZATION> said interest income on the <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Marianas</LOCATION> bonds isn't exempt from taxes. 
The tax-exempt status is the major selling point of municipal bonds. 
New York-based <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION> responded that it believes the issues were made validly and that the interest income is tax exempt. 

   In addition to <PERSON>Mr. Goldberg</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>Matthews &amp; Wright</ORGANIZATION> officials who could be charged by the <ORGANIZATION>SEC</ORGANIZATION> are Chairman <PERSON>George Benoit</PERSON> and <PERSON>Roger Burns</PERSON>, treasurer and chief financial officer. 
Also listed is <PERSON>Bernard Althoff</PERSON>, who is identified as the firm's outside corporate counsel. 

</TEXT>
