<HEAD>Ada Wins Second Term as Guam Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGANA, Guam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. <PERSON>Joseph Ada</PERSON> posted an easy victory
<DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, making the Republican the first governor to win
back-to-back terms in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> territory's history.
   With all 76 precincts reporting, <ORGANIZATION>Ada</ORGANIZATION> received 20,677 votes to
Democrat <PERSON>Madeleine Bordallo</PERSON>'s 15,688 votes, the <ORGANIZATION>Guam Election
Commission</ORGANIZATION> reported.
   Final official tallies are expected <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, the commission
said.
   The abortion issue was not a factor in the vote, as both
candidates oppose abortion and support a court challenge to a
decision striking down the territory's restrictive abortion law.
   Bordallo, the first woman and non-native Guamanian to run for
governor, is the widow of former Gov. <PERSON>Ricardo Bordallo</PERSON>. Her husband
committed suicide <DATE>Jan. 30</DATE>, one day before he was to begin an
18-month federal prison term in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>. He was not in office at
the time of his death.
   In the territory's congressional election, Republican <PERSON>Ben Blaz</PERSON>
won a fourth term as a non-voting delegate, defeating Democrat <PERSON>Ben
Pagelinan</PERSON> by 21,390 to 16,437.
</TEXT>
